BENIN  – The Chairman of Independent Petroleum Marketers Association of Nigeria (IPMAN), Benin Deport Unit, Alhaji Baba Abdul saliu, has lamented the inability of the Federal Government to put any of Nigeria’s refineries into production. He said it is a shame for Nigeria to be importing refined petroleum products, a country known to be one of the major oil producing nations in the world. Alhaji Abdul saliu, who spoke with journalist, soon after his inauguration as the new chairman of the Benin Deport Unit, however, promised to partner with the Government and other relevant authorities to ensure the refinery works again. GTCO PLC Acquires IOPM, IOFM Held By Investment One Financial… Mouka Rewards Business Partners, Staff With Over N110m… While promising to offer the necessary advice that will be beneficiary to the government and the people, the IPMAN Chairman, also promised to reposition the union to ensure that the members enjoy the benefits of their membership. The IPMAN new executives which run the affairs of the union for the next three years was inaugurated after the Annual General Meeting (AGM) of the union which took place in Benin City with all the members from Edo North, Central, South and Kogi fully represented Those elected were Alhaji Baba Abdul Saliu as Chairman, Mr Godwin Eke Iroghama vice chairman, Elder Sylvanus Osoliase , secretary and Madam Angelina Aigbokhai as the assistant secretary. Others are Mr Pius Ikhuenbo, financial secretary, Mr Michael Ogiamen as treasurer, Public Relations Officer, Otunba Olarenwaju, Auditor ,Mr Chucks Aghalor ,legal adviser , Mr Charles Omere and Mr Monday Irhabor as an ex-official.